## Security mapping (as required)
- **SQL injection** → parameterized prepared statements only (`repositories.js`)
- **Passwords** → bcrypt, cost 12, per-password salt; constant-time login compare; session regenerated on login (anti-fixation)
- **XSS** → client renders via `textContent`/`value` only, plus strict CSP (no inline JS/CSS)
- **CSRF** → per-session synchronizer token required via `X-CSRF-Token` on all state-changing requests; `SameSite=Lax`
- **Access control / IDOR** → every REST route and socket event re-checks rights against the DB; returns 404 (not 403) for inaccessible docs
- **Session cookies** → `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` when `SECURE_COOKIES=true`
- **Headers** → helmet; **rate limiting** on auth; **input validation** via express-validator; **no stack traces** leaked; **secrets** from env only

## Two things to note
- I used **bcryptjs** (pure JS) instead of native `bcrypt` so install won't fail on a Windows toolchain — it's still bcrypt, satisfying the requirement.
- `better-sqlite3` is native but normally pulls a prebuilt binary; the README notes the build-tools fallback if your Node version lacks one.

